d, Devon, England":"Moretonhampstead, Devon, England","Gainsborough Old Hall, Gainsborough, Lincolnshire, England":"Gainsborough, Lincolnshire, Engleska, United Kingdom","Morston Manor, Halberton, Devonshire, England":"Halberton, Devon, England"},"cs":{"1360–1420":"1360–1420","1355–1380":"1355–1380","1379–1469":"1379–1469","1383–1444":"1383–1444","1334–Male":"1334–Zesnulý","1338–Female":"1338–Zesnulá","after 1379":"po 1379","1338":"1338","1469":"1469","1379":"1379","1334":"1334","1444":"1444","1355":"1355","1420":"1420","1383":"1383","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","Blackpool, Lancashire, England":"Blackpool, Lancashire, Anglie","Marston, Lincolnshire, England":"Marston, Lincolnshire, Anglie","Moretonhampstead, Devon, England":"Moretonhampstead, Devon, Anglie","Gainsborough Old Hall, Gainsborough, Lincolnshire, England":"Gainsborough, Lincolnshire, Anglie, United Kingdom","Morston Manor, Halberton, Devonshire, England":"Halberton, Devon, Anglie"},"da":{"1360–1420":"1360–1420","1355–1380":"1355–1380","1379–1469":"1379–1469","1383–1444":"1383–1444","1334–Male":"1334–Afdød","1338–Female":"1338–Afdød","after 1379":"efter 1379","1338":"1338","1469":"1469","1379":"1379","1334":"1334","1444":"1444","1355":"1355","1420":"1420","1383":"1383","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","Blackpool, Lancashire, England":"Blackpool, Lancashire, England","Marston, Lincolnshire, England":"Marston, Lincolnshire, England","Moretonhampstead, Devon, England":"Moretonhampstead, Devon, England","Gainsborough Old Hall, Gainsborough, Lincolnshire, England":"Gainsborough, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Morston Manor, Halberton, Devonshire, England":"Halberton, Devon, England"},"nl":{"1360–1420":"1360–1420","1355–1380":"1355–1380","1379–1469":"1379–1469","1383–1444":"1383–1444","1334–Male":"1334–Overleden","1338–Female":"1338–Overleden","after 1379":"na 1379","1338":"1338","1469":"1469","1379":"1379","1334":"1334","1444":"1444","1355":"1355","1420":"1420","1383":"1383","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","Blackpool, Lancashire, England":"Blackpool, Lancashire, England","Marston, Lincolnshire, England":"Marston, Lincolnshire, England","Moretonhampstead, Devon, England":"Moretonhampstead, Devon, England","Gainsborough Old Hall, Gainsborough, Lincolnshire, England":"Gainsborough, Lincolnshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Morston Manor, Halberton, Devonshire, England":"Halberton, Devon, England"},"en":{"1360–1420":"1360–1420","1355–1380":"1355–1380","1379–1469":"1379–1469","1383–1444":"1383–1444","1334–Male":"1334–Deceased","1338–Female":"1338–Deceased","after 1379":"after 1379","1338":"1338","1469":"1469","1379":"1379","1334":"1334","1444":"1444","1355":"1355","1420":"1420","1383":"1383","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","Blackpool, Lancashire, England":"Blackpool, Lancashire, England","Marston, Lincolnshire, England":"Marston, Lincolnshire, England","Moretonhampstead, Devon, England":"Moretonhampstead, Devon, England","Gainsborough Old Hall, Gainsborough, Lincolnshire, England":"Gainsborough, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Morston Manor, Halberton, Devonshire, England":"Halberton, Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Tucker","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (southwestern): occupational name from Middle English <i>tuker(e)</i>, <i>toker(e)</i> ‘tucker, fuller’, a derivative of <i>tuken</i> ‘to torment, beat’ (Old English <i>tūcian</i>), for someone who fulled and finished cloth. This name for the occupation was characteristic of the West Country. Compare   Fuller   and   Walker   and see also   Tuckerman  .","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Tuachair</b> ‘descendant of <i>Tuachar</i>’, a personal name composed of the elements <i>tuath</i> ‘people’ + <i>car</i> ‘dear, beloved’.","Americanized form of Jewish <b>Tocker</b> or <b>Toker</b> (see   Tokarz  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Tooker","meanings":["English (Devon) and Irish: variant of   Tucker  ."]},{"name":"Tuckerman","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>tuker(e)</i>, <i>toker(e)</i> ‘tucker, fuller’ (see   Tucker   1) + <i>-man</i>, either for a tucker, or for his servant or assistant."]},{"name":"Fuller","meanings":["English: occupational name for a dresser of cloth, from Middle English <i>fuller</i> ‘fuller of cloth’ (partly from Old English <i>fullere</i>, partly from Old French <i>fouleor</i>, <i>foleur</i>, Latin <i>fullo</i>). Raw cloth had to be fulled, i.e. scoured, cleansed, and thickened by beating or trampling it in water, a process also known as <i>walking</i> or <i>tucking</i>, hence the surnames   Walker   and   Tucker   alongside <i>Fuller</i>. These three terms and surnames are characteristic of different parts of England. In general, in Middle English, <i>Fuller</i> is southern and eastern, while <i>Walker</i> belongs to the west and north and <i>Tucker</i> is southwestern. Compare   Fullen  .","English: variant of   Fullard   with loss of <i>-d</i>.","German (<b>Füller</b>): occupational name for a person whose work involved filling, such as a dauber, or a nickname for a gourmand or glutton. Compare   Filler  ."]},{"name":"Swinger","meanings":["English: occupational name, perhaps for a fuller, who finished cloth by beating it and stretching it on tenters. Middle English swyngere is not independently recorded but it appears to be an agent derivative of Middle English <i>swingen</i> ‘to beat, strike, punish, afflict (something)’. Compare the synonymous   Tucker  , an agent derivative of Middle English <i>tuken</i> ‘to torment, beat’. The earliest bearers of the name <i>Swinger</i> were wealthy townsmen.","In some instances probably an Americanized form of German and Jewish (Ashkenazic)   Schwinger  , or German <b>Zwinger</b>, a nickname from Middle High German <i>zwinger</i> ‘oppressor’."]}]},{"name":"Isabelle","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , now in frequent use in the English-speaking world."],"variants":[{"name":"Isabel","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":22,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Isabelle Tucker was born in 1360, in Moretonhampstead, Devon, England, her father, Herman Tucker, was 26 and her mother, Baroness Laura Selma Lehman, was 23. She had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Sir William Gambon Of Moreston. She died in 1420, in Blackpool, Lancashire, England, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1360–1420":"1360–1420","1355–1380":"1355–1380","1379–1469":"1379–1469","1383–1444":"1383–1444","1334–Male":"1334–Surnud","1338–Female":"1338–Surnud","after 1379":"pärast 1379","1338":"1338","1469":"1469","1379":"1379","1334":"1334","1444":"1444","1355":"1355","1420":"1420","1383":"1383","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","Blackpool, Lancashire, England":"Blackpool, Lancashire, England","Marston, Lincolnshire, England":"Marston, Lincolnshire, England","Moretonhampstead, Devon, Engla